    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nOn Windows, pressing `Ctrl+C` in terminal mode (`:terminal`) does not send an interrupt signal to running child processes. The keypress is received by the terminal (typing `Ctrl+C` at an idle PowerShell prompt shows `^C` and starts a new prompt line), but when a program is actively running (e.g. `ping localhost -t`, `Start-Sleep 30`), `Ctrl+C` has no effect — the process keeps running.\nThis also cannot be worked around via the Lua API. Sending `\\x03` directly to the terminal channel with `vim.api.nvim_chan_send(chan, \"\\x03\")` or `vim.fn.chansend(chan, \"\\x03\")` also does NOT stop the running process, confirming the issue is at the ConPTY/channel level, not the keymap level.\nThis worked correctly in v0.11.x on the same machine and terminal.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n```\nnvim --clean\n:terminal pwsh.exe -NoLogo\ni\nping localhost -t\n<Press Ctrl+C>\n```\nObserve: ping continues running, `Ctrl+C` has no effect.\nFor additional confirmation that the issue is at the channel level:\n```\n1. Press `Ctrl+\\ Ctrl+n` to exit terminal mode\n2. Run: `:lua vim.fn.chansend(vim.bo.channel, \"\\x03\")`\n3. Press `i` to re-enter terminal mode\n4. Observe: ping is still running\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nPressing Ctrl+C in terminal mode should send an interrupt signal (CTRL_C_EVENT) to the foreground process running in the terminal, causing it to terminate (same behavior as v0.11.x and standalone terminal).\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0 Release, LuaJIT 2.1.1774638290\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, not applicable (Vim does not use ConPTY on Windows in the same way)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11 (NT 10.0.26200.0)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nwinget install Neovim.Neovim",
